Communicate Data Funding ( USA YouTube dataset)¶

Let's have a look at some features' ranking first¶

The top 15 views of video¶

The best indicator for virality would be the counting on views.¶

In [14]:
top10(youtube, 'views', 15)

No wonder Childish Gambino is Grammy Winner, the official video had over 200 million views, till now, it has 479 million views, 7.6 million likes. Beside it, most of top 15 videos are music video, I could assume Music is one the most popular category.¶

Top 15 likes of video¶

Along with views, we could conclude if the video is popular or not.¶

In [15]:
top10(youtube, 'likes', 15)

Top 15 dislikes of video¶

I believe only first two videos are truely hated by audiences. Others are due to the highly viewed by people, since dislikes and views are correlated.¶

In [16]:
top10(youtube, 'dislikes', 15)

Top 15 comments of video¶

Comments could be positive, negative and neutral, so it can’t help to decide the popularity pretty much. However, I believe comments reflects views.¶

In [17]:
top10(youtube, 'comment_count', 15)

As I said, comments are unable to reflect trueth about the popularity. The most commented one -- So Sorry, is the most disliked one, and the second -- BTS 'FAKE LOVE' Official MV is the most like one .¶

Most influenced publisher¶

Rate distribution¶

Here's a combination rate distribution for views, likes, dislikes, comments. All of four are bell-shaped, which is normal distributed.¶

In [28]:
youtube['like_rate']=youtube['likes']/youtube['views']*100
youtube['dislike_rate']=youtube['dislikes']/youtube['views']*100
youtube['comment_rate']=youtube['comment_count']/youtube['views']*100

plt.figure(figsize = (12,8))
plt.title('Rate distribution', fontsize = 20)
sns.distplot(youtube['like_rate'],color='red',hist=False,label='Likes')
sns.distplot(youtube['dislike_rate'],color='green',hist=False,label='Dislikes')
sns.distplot(youtube['comment_rate'],color='blue',hist=False,label='Comments')
plt.xlabel(' ')
plt.show()

From above graphs, 15th is the lucky day for videos to trend. Based on month, winter is the hot season for publishing, as well as trending, I assume this is due to holiday season.¶

Heatmap of trending duration on different category¶

Besides the number of videos, the trending time of the video is also an important indicator to its popularity.¶

In [37]:
youtube= pd.merge(youtube, duration, on = 'title')
fig,ax=plt.subplots(figsize=(12,8))
sns.heatmap(youtube.groupby(['category','trending_duration']).count()['video_id'].unstack(), cmap = 'viridis_r')
plt.title('Trending duration on Category', fontsize = 15)
plt.xlabel('trending duration')
plt.show()

The bar chart of category shows the most popular is Entertainment (not Music!), then comes with Music, Howto & Style…However, here we also look at the trending time for each category to define the popularity. Still, the Entertainment is the most popular category, the darkest cell implies there are most trending videos in Entertainment, and some videos's trending duration are more than 30 days. Then I also can conclude that Music, Howto & Style, News & Politics and Comedy are also welcomed.¶

The impact of views on liks vs. dislikes¶

In [43]:
plt.figure(figsize = (16,8))
plt.grid()
plt.scatter(data = youtube, x = 'likes', y = 'dislikes', s = youtube['views']/100000, edgecolors='black', alpha = 0.6)
plt.title('Views on Likes to Dislikes', fontsize = 20)
plt.xlabel('Likes', fontsize = 20)
plt.ylabel('Dislikes', fontsize = 20)

size = [1000000, 5000000, 10000000, 50000000, 100000000, 150000000, 200000000, 250000000]
col = sns.color_palette()[0]
leg_obj = []
for s in size:
    leg_obj.append(plt.scatter([],[], s=s/100000, color = col, alpha = 0.6, edgecolors='black'))
plt.legend(leg_obj, size, title = 'Views',prop= {'size': 18})
plt.show()

As was expected, the views impact does exist. for majority videos, views sizes are medium, more likes do lead more dislikes, but in a small amount compares to likes.¶

Relationship between each variables (views, likes, dislikes, comments)¶

In [44]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,8))
sns.heatmap(youtube[['views', 'likes', 'dislikes', 'comment_count']].corr(), annot=True, cmap = 'viridis_r')
plt.title('Correlations')
plt.show()

1) likes and views are highly correlated¶

2) likes and comments are highly correlated¶

3) comments and views are moderately correlated¶

4) dislikes and views are low correlated¶

5) dislikes and likes are low correlated¶
